subsection.p:
The definition of the derivative allows us to develop a new differentiation rule.
The key property necessary for the exponential function is a consequence of the properties of exponents,
 \exp_b(x+y) = b^{x+y} = b^x \cdot b^y = \exp_b(x) \cdot \exp_b(y).
Using these properties

   \exp_b'(x) &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{\exp_b(x+h) - \exp_b(x)}{h} 
   &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{b^{x+h} - b^x}{h} 
   &= \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{b^x b^h - b^x}{h} 
   &= \lim_{h \to 0} \exp_b(x) \cdot \frac{b^h-1}{h} 
   &= \exp_b(x) \cdot \lim_{h \to 0} \frac{b^{h}-1}{h}.

statement.p:
         Find the derivatives of the following functions.


f(x) = e^{5x} 

g(x) = e^{x^3} 

h(x) = e^{x^2-4x}

solution.p:
In each case, we will identify the formula u(x) and then apply the chain rule.





      For f(x) = e^{5x}, we have u(x)=5x so that f(x) = e^u.
      We will use u'(x)=5.
      The chain rule gives:

          f'(x) &= \frac{d}{dx}[e^{5x}] 
           & \underset{(u=5x)}{=} \frac{d}{dx}[e^u] \underset{(u=5x)}{=} e^u \frac{du}{dx} 
           &= e^{5x} \cdot 5 = 5e^{5x} 

      So f'(x) = 5e^{5x}.






      The function g(x) = e^{x^3} involves a composition with u(x)=x^3
      such that u'(x)=3x^2.

        g'(x) &= \frac{d}{dx}[e^{x^3}] 
         &\underset{(u=x^3)}{=} \frac{d}{dx}[e^u] \underset{(u=x^3)}{=} e^u \frac{du}{dx} 
         &= e^{x^3} \cdot (3x^2) = 3x^2 e^{x^3} 

      Thus g'(x) = 3x^2e^{x^3}.






      The function h(x) = e^{x^2-4x} involves a composition with u(x)=x^2-4x
      such that u'(x)=2x-4.

        h'(x) &= \frac{d}{dx}[e^{x^2-4x}] 
         &\underset{(u=x^2-4x)}{=} \frac{d}{dx}[e^u] \underset{(u=x^2-4x)}{=} e^u \frac{du}{dx} 
         &= e^{x^2-4x} \cdot (2x-4) = (2x-4) e^{x^2-4x} 

      Thus h'(x) = (2x-4)e^{x^2-4x}.
